Big Data Analysis and Prediction of Football Players' Performances, Market Values, and Team Results ⚽️🏟️¶

Project Overview¶

This project aims to utilize Big Data techniques with PySpark to analyze and predict various aspects of football, focusing on player performance, market values, and team results. The dataset used for this project is sourced from Transfermarkt and includes data on top six European competitions:

  • Bundesliga
  • La Liga
  • Premier League
  • Serie A
  • Ligue 1
  • UEFA Champions League 🏆 (only for predicting club victories using Multiclass Classification & conformal prediction)

First, we import most of the libraries we'll be using throught the analysis.

Some extra Data using User Defined Function¶

I’ve defined a country_data dictionary that stores flags and ISO alpha codes for different countries. I’ve also created two UDFs, get_flag_url_udf and get_iso_alpha_udf, to quickly retrieve the flag URL and ISO code for any given country. The get_country_info function helps pull this data from the dictionary when needed, allowing me to dynamically map country data during processing.

def get_country_info(country, field):
    if country in country_data:
        return country_data[country].get(field, None)
    return None

get_flag_url_udf = udf(lambda country: get_country_info(country, 'flag_url'), StringType())
get_iso_alpha_udf = udf(lambda country: get_country_info(country, 'iso_alpha'), StringType())

Player Performance Analysis:¶

I did several joins to merge the necessary data from multiple DataFrames. Here’s a brief explanation of each step:

  • df_appearances_games: I joined the appearances dataset with the games dataset on game_id to retrieve player appearances along with match details such as date, season, and game ID.

  • df_appearances_games_competitions: Next, I joined this result with the competitions dataset to add competition details like the competition code, name, and country.

  • df_players_perf: Then, I merged the resulting DataFrame with the clubs dataset to include information about the player's current club, and finally joined it with the players dataset to get detailed player attributes like their name, position, and market value.

  • df_clubs_total: In another join, I combined appearances with games and clubs to calculate total team metrics such as the number of goals, assists, and additional club information like market value, average age, and squad size.

  • df_clubs_players_cost: Finally, I joined the clubs and players datasets to compute the overall cost and player statistics per club, and I linked it with the competitions dataset to capture the country associated with each competition.

df_appearances_games = df_appearances_f.join(
    df_games_f,
    df_appearances_f.game_id == df_games_f.game_id,
    how="inner"
).select(
    df_appearances_f.player_id,
    df_appearances_f.player_name,
    df_appearances_f.competition_id,
    df_appearances_f.player_club_id,
    df_appearances_f.goals,
    df_appearances_f.assists,
    df_appearances_f.minutes_played,
    df_games_f.date,
    df_games_f.season,
    df_games_f.game_id
)

# then with the competitions dataframe to get the name of the players current competition
df_appearances_games_competitions = df_appearances_games.join(
    df_competitions_f,
    df_appearances_games.competition_id == df_competitions_f.competition_id,
    how="inner"
).select(
    df_appearances_games["*"],
    df_competitions_f.competition_code,
    df_competitions_f.country_name,
    df_competitions_f.name.alias("competition_name")
)

# then with clubs to get the clubs of the player
df_players_perf = df_appearances_games_competitions.join(
    df_clubs_f,
    df_appearances_games_competitions.player_club_id == df_clubs_f.club_id,
    how="inner"
).select(
    df_clubs_f.name.alias("player_club"),
    df_appearances_games_competitions["*"]
)

df_players_perf = df_players_perf.join(
    df_players_f,

KNN VS KNN+LSH of Player based on their performances¶

We'll apply a logarithmic transformation to our data to avoid issues related to the large differences in scale between the variables. This transformation helps stabilize variance, making the data more suitable for clustering !

In [16]:
from pyspark.sql import functions as F


cluster_player_perf = df_players_perf.groupBy("player_id", "player_name", "country_of_citizenship", "position") \
    .agg(
        F.sum("goals").alias("total_goals"),
        F.countDistinct("game_id").alias("total_games"),
        F.sum("assists").alias("total_assists"),
        F.avg('market_value_in_eur').alias("avg_market_value"),
        F.avg('minutes_played').alias("avg_minutes_played_per_game")
    ) \
    .withColumn("log_total_goals", F.log1p("total_goals")) \
    .withColumn("log_total_games", F.log1p("total_games")) \
    .withColumn("log_total_assists", F.log1p("total_assists")) \
    .withColumn("log_avg_market_value", F.log1p("avg_market_value")) \
    .withColumn("log_avg_minutes_played", F.log1p("avg_minutes_played_per_game")) \
    .select("player_id", "player_name", "country_of_citizenship", "position",
            "log_total_goals", "log_total_games", "log_total_assists",
            "log_avg_market_value", "log_avg_minutes_played") \
    .orderBy(F.desc("log_total_goals"))

cluster_player_perf = cluster_player_perf.dropna(subset=["log_total_goals", "log_total_games", "log_total_assists", "log_avg_market_value", "log_avg_minutes_played"])

# Show the result
cluster_player_perf.show()

from pyspark.sql import functions as F
from pyspark.sql.types import FloatType
from pyspark.sql.window import Window
import time

start_time = time.time()

#joueur de référence (exemple Ronaldo, player_id=8198)
player_of_interest = vector_df.filter(F.col("player_id") == 8198).select("features").first()['features']

distance_udf = F.udf(lambda features: float(features.squared_distance(player_of_interest)), FloatType())

knn_classic_df = vector_df.withColumn("distance", distance_udf(F.col("features")))

window = Window.partitionBy("distance").orderBy("distance")
knn_classic = knn_classic_df.withColumn("rank", F.row_number().over(window)).filter(F.col("rank") <= 5)

end_time = time.time()
print(f"Temps d'exécution pour KNN Classique : {end_time - start_time} secondes")

knn_classic.select("player_id", "player_name", "features", "distance").show(truncate=False)

from pyspark.ml.feature import BucketedRandomProjectionLSH
from pyspark.sql import functions as F


start_time = time.time()

# LSH pour la similarité cosinus et KNN
lsh = BucketedRandomProjectionLSH(
    inputCol="features",
    outputCol="hashes",
    bucketLength=2.0,
    numHashTables=3
)
lsh_model = lsh.fit(vector_df)
player_of_interest = vector_df.filter(F.col("player_id") == 8198).select("features") # choix d'un joueur de référence ronaldo
nearest_neighbors = lsh_model.approxNearestNeighbors(vector_df, player_of_interest.first()['features'], numNearestNeighbors=5) # Recherche des voisins les plus proches (KNN avec LSH)


end_time = time.time()
print(f"Temps d'exécution pour LSH + KNN : {end_time - start_time} secondes")

nearest_neighbors.select("player_id", "player_name", "features", "distCol").show(truncate=False)

1. Temps d'exécution :¶

  • Le KNN classique a pris environ 0.77 secondes pour trouver les 5 voisins les plus proches de Cristiano Ronaldo.
  • Le KNN avec LSH a pris environ 0.71 secondes, soit légèrement moins de temps pour obtenir les résultats.

Interprétation : Bien que LSH soit généralement plus rapide, dans ce cas, la différence de temps entre les deux approches est très faible, probablement en raison de la taille des données. Cependant, sur des ensembles de données beaucoup plus grands, LSH devrait montrer un gain de temps plus significatif, car il est conçu pour accélérer la recherche de similarités dans des bases de données massives. ==> trade off

2. Résultats des voisins les plus proches :¶

KNN Classique :¶

Les 5 joueurs les plus proches de Cristiano Ronaldo selon la distance euclidienne sont :

  1. Cristiano Ronaldo (distance = 0.0)
  2. Robert Lewandowski (distance = 0.0499)
  3. Karim Benzema (distance = 0.2838)
  4. Antoine Griezmann (distance = 0.7234)
  5. Sergio Agüero (distance = 1.0217)

KNN avec LSH :¶

Les 5 joueurs les plus proches de Cristiano Ronaldo selon LSH (approximation de la similarité cosinus) sont :

  1. Cristiano Ronaldo (distance = 0.0)
  2. Robert Lewandowski (distance = 0.2233)
  3. Karim Benzema (distance = 0.5327)
  4. Antoine Griezmann (distance = 0.8505)
  5. Sergio Agüero (distance = 1.0108)

Interprétation des résultats : Les deux méthodes ont trouvé les mêmes joueurs comme voisins les plus proches de Cristiano Ronaldo, ce qui montre que LSH a bien fonctionné en approximant la similarité tout en étant plus rapide. Les distances dans le cas du KNN classique sont légèrement différentes de celles obtenues avec LSH, mais l'ordre des voisins est identique. Cela signifie que pour ce type de données, LSH parvient à donner des résultats très proches de ceux d'une recherche KNN classique, tout en optimisant la vitesse.

3. Précision vs Performance :¶

  • Le KNN classique effectue une recherche exacte en calculant directement la distance euclidienne entre les vecteurs de caractéristiques de chaque joueur. Cela garantit une grande précision dans les distances, mais à un coût potentiellement élevé en termes de temps de calcul pour de plus grands ensembles de données.
  • Le KNN avec LSH utilise une approche approximative pour trouver les voisins proches en fonction de la similarité cosinus. Cette méthode est plus rapide et plus efficace, surtout avec des bases de données massives, mais peut introduire une légère approximation dans les distances.

Market Value and Performance¶

We will experiment with two methods: one utilizing Spark optimizations and the other without, both applied to a Decision Tree classifier with cross-validation, to compare their performance.

import time
from pyspark.ml.feature import StringIndexer, VectorAssembler, MinMaxScaler
from pyspark.ml.classification import DecisionTreeClassifier
from pyspark.ml.evaluation import MulticlassClassificationEvaluator
from pyspark.ml.tuning import CrossValidator, ParamGridBuilder
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline
from pyspark.sql import functions as F

start_time = time.time()

decision_tree_player_perf = df_players_perf.groupBy("player_id", "player_name", "country_of_citizenship", "position") \
    .agg(
        F.sum("goals").alias("total_goals"),
        F.countDistinct("game_id").alias("total_games"),
        F.sum("assists").alias("total_assists"),
        F.avg('market_value_in_eur').alias("avg_market_value"),
        F.avg('minutes_played').alias("avg_minutes_played_per_game")
    )

decision_tree_player_perf = decision_tree_player_perf.dropna(subset=["total_goals", "total_games", "total_assists", "avg_market_value", "avg_minutes_played_per_game"])

print(f"Data aggregation completed in {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")

# construction des features
indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol="position", outputCol="label")
assembler = VectorAssembler(
    inputCols=["total_goals", "total_games", "total_assists", "avg_market_value", "avg_minutes_played_per_game"],
    outputCol="features"
)
# normalisation
scaler = MinMaxScaler(inputCol="features", outputCol="scaled_features")

# creation du classifier
dt_classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(labelCol="label", featuresCol="scaled_features")

# la pipeline
pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[indexer, assembler, scaler, dt_classifier])

# grille de paramètres
paramGrid = ParamGridBuilder() \
    .addGrid(dt_classifier.maxDepth, [3, 5]) \
    .addGrid(dt_classifier.minInstancesPerNode, [1, 3]) \
    .build()

# cross validation
crossval = CrossValidator(estimator=pipeline,
                          estimatorParamMaps=paramGrid,
                          evaluator=MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="label", predictionCol="prediction", metricName="accuracy"),
                          numFolds=5)


train_data, test_data = decision_tree_player_perf.randomSplit([0.8, 0.2], seed=42)

start_time = time.time()
cvModel = crossval.fit(train_data)
print(f"Model training with cross-validation completed in {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")

start_time = time.time()
predictions = cvModel.transform(test_data)
print(f"Prediction on test data completed in {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")

start_time = time.time()
evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="label", predictionCol="prediction", metricName="accuracy")
accuracy = evaluator.evaluate(predictions)
print(f"Evaluation completed in {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")

print(f"Test Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")

import findspark
findspark.init()

from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql import functions as F
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline
from pyspark.ml.feature import StringIndexer, VectorAssembler, MinMaxScaler
from pyspark.ml.classification import DecisionTreeClassifier
from pyspark.ml.evaluation import MulticlassClassificationEvaluator
from pyspark.ml.tuning import CrossValidator, ParamGridBuilder
import time

# Initialiser la session Spark
spark = SparkSession.builder.appName("Football Players Decision Tree Optimized").getOrCreate()

start_time = time.time()
decision_tree_player_perf_opti = df_players_perf.groupBy("player_id", "player_name", "country_of_citizenship", "position") \
    .agg(
        F.sum("goals").alias("total_goals"),
        F.countDistinct("game_id").alias("total_games"),
        F.sum("assists").alias("total_assists"),
        F.avg('market_value_in_eur').alias("avg_market_value"),
        F.avg('minutes_played').alias("avg_minutes_played_per_game")
    )
decision_tree_player_perf_opti = decision_tree_player_perf_opti.dropna(subset=["total_goals", "total_games", "total_assists", "avg_market_value", "avg_minutes_played_per_game"])

print(f"Data aggregation completed in {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")

# construction des features
label_indexer_opti = StringIndexer(inputCol="position", outputCol="label_indexed")
assembler_opti = VectorAssembler(
    inputCols=["total_goals", "total_games", "total_assists", "avg_market_value", "avg_minutes_played_per_game"],
    outputCol="features"
)
scaler_opti = MinMaxScaler(inputCol="features", outputCol="scaled_features")

# le classifier
dt_classifier_op = DecisionTreeClassifier(labelCol="label_indexed", featuresCol="scaled_features")

# la pipeline
pipeline_op = Pipeline(stages=[label_indexer_opti, assembler_opti, scaler_opti, dt_classifier_op])

# grille de paramètres et validation croisée
paramGrid_op = ParamGridBuilder() \
    .addGrid(dt_classifier_op.maxDepth, [3, 5]) \
    .addGrid(dt_classifier_op.minInstancesPerNode, [1, 3]) \
    .build()

crossval_op = CrossValidator(estimator=pipeline_op,
                          estimatorParamMaps=paramGrid_op,
                          evaluator=MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="label_indexed", predictionCol="prediction", metricName="accuracy"),
                          numFolds=5)

# split
train_data_op, test_data_op = decision_tree_player_perf_opti.randomSplit([0.8, 0.2], seed=42)

# Partitionner les données pour une meilleure parallélisation
train_data_op = train_data_op.repartition(100)
test_data_op = test_data_op.repartition(100)

# Réglage du parallélisme des tâches
spark.conf.set("spark.default.parallelism", "100")

start_time = time.time()
cvModel_op = crossval_op.fit(train_data_op)
print(f"Model training with cross-validation completed in {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")

best_model_op = cvModel_op.bestModel

start_time = time.time()
predictions_op = best_model_op.transform(test_data_op)
print(f"Prediction on test data completed in {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")

start_time = time.time()
evaluator_op = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="label_indexed", predictionCol="prediction", metricName="accuracy")
accuracy = evaluator_op.evaluate(predictions_op)
print(f"Evaluation completed in {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")
print(f"Test Accuracy after optimization: {accuracy:.2f}")

Data aggregation completed in 0.04 seconds
Model training with cross-validation completed in 348.67 seconds
Prediction on test data completed in 0.10 seconds
Evaluation completed in 5.41 seconds
Test Accuracy after optimization: 0.58

La principale optimisation que j'ai apportée concerne l'utilisation explicite des partitions dans le second code.

Les partitions permettent à Spark de diviser les données en segments plus petits, ce qui facilite leur traitement en parallèle sur plusieurs nœuds du cluster. Grâce à cette répartition, chaque partition peut être traitée indépendamment, augmentant ainsi le parallélisme et réduisant les temps d'exécution. Dans le second code, j'ai ajouté repartition(100) pour forcer la division des données en 100 partitions, optimisant ainsi la parallélisation, contrairement au premier code qui utilise la partition par défaut.

Différences de performance en termes de temps¶

  • Temps d'entraînement :

    • Sans partition explicite : 735.65 secondes
    • Avec partition optimisée : 348.67 secondes
    • Résultat : Le temps d'entraînement est réduit de plus de 50 %.

  • Temps de prédiction :

    • Sans partition explicite : 0.33 secondes
    • Avec partition optimisée : 0.10 secondes

# UDF function to format the market value
def format_market_value(market_value):
    if market_value is not None:
        return f"{int(market_value):,}".replace(",", " ") + " euros"
    return "0 euros"

format_market_value_udf = F.udf(format_market_value, StringType())

df_player_totals = df_players_perf.groupBy(
    "player_id", "player_name", "position"
).agg(
    F.sum("goals").alias("total_goals"),
    F.countDistinct("game_id").alias("total_matches"),
    F.avg("market_value_in_eur").alias("average_market_value_in_eur")
)

# the goal average
df_player_totals = df_player_totals.withColumn(
    "goal_average", F.col("total_goals") / F.col("total_matches")

df_player_totals = df_player_totals.withColumn("log_total_goals", F.log1p("total_goals")) \

from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler
from pyspark.ml.regression import LinearRegression

# drop nulls
df_regression = df_player_totals.dropna(subset=["log_avg_market_value", "goal_average"])
df_regression = df_regression.filter(F.col("position") == "Attack")

assembler = VectorAssembler(
    inputCols=["log_avg_market_value"],
    outputCol="features"
)

df_regression = assembler.transform(df_regression)

# we train
lr = LinearRegression(featuresCol="features", labelCol="goal_average")
lr_model = lr.fit(df_regression)

# results
print(f"Coefficients: {lr_model.coefficients}")
print(f"Intercept: {lr_model.intercept}")

# evaluation
training_summary = lr_model.summary
print(f"R-squared: {training_summary.r2}")
print(f"Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): {training_summary.rootMeanSquaredError}")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {training_summary.meanAbsoluteError}")

# showing predictions
predictions = lr_model.transform(df_regression)
predictions.select("player_id", "player_name", "log_avg_market_value", "goal_average", "prediction").show(10, truncate=False)

from pybloom_live import BloomFilter
from pyspark.sql import functions as F

# initializing bloom filter for game ids
bloom_filter_game_id = BloomFilter(capacity=100000, error_rate=0.001)

# udf function to check if the id in already in the filter
def is_game_duplicate(game_id):
    if game_id in bloom_filter_game_id:
        return True
    else:
        bloom_filter_game_id.add(game_id)
        return False

# saving udf
is_game_duplicate_udf = F.udf(lambda x: is_game_duplicate(x))

# filtering
top_5_leagues = ['FR1', 'IT1', 'GB1', 'L1', 'ES1']
df_top_5_leagues = df_clubs_total.filter(F.col("competition_id").isin(top_5_leagues))

top_clubs_total = top_clubs_total.limit(10)
top_club_ids = [row['club_id'] for row in top_clubs_total.collect()]


# adding the column to know if a row is duplicated or not
df_top_5_leagues_filtered = df_top_5_leagues.withColumn(
    "is_duplicate",
    is_game_duplicate_udf(F.col("game_id"))
).filter(F.col("is_duplicate") == False)

In [ ]:
from pyspark.sql import functions as F
from pyspark.sql import Window

# Calcul de la moyenne et de la variance pour la méthode avec le filtre de Bloom
mean_bloom = top_clubs_by_year_bloom.agg(F.mean('average_goals_per_match')).collect()[0][0]
variance_bloom = top_clubs_by_year_bloom.agg(F.variance('average_goals_per_match')).collect()[0][0]

# Pour la médiane, il faut utiliser une fenêtre et calculer la valeur médiane manuellement
window_spec = Window.orderBy('average_goals_per_match')
count_bloom = top_clubs_by_year_bloom.count()

if count_bloom % 2 == 0:
    # Si le nombre de lignes est pair, la médiane est la moyenne des deux valeurs centrales
    median_bloom = top_clubs_by_year_bloom.withColumn('row_num', F.row_number().over(window_spec)) \
        .filter((F.col('row_num') == count_bloom // 2) | (F.col('row_num') == count_bloom // 2 + 1)) \
        .agg(F.mean('average_goals_per_match')).collect()[0][0]
else:
    # Si le nombre de lignes est impair, la médiane est la valeur centrale
    median_bloom = top_clubs_by_year_bloom.withColumn('row_num', F.row_number().over(window_spec)) \
        .filter(F.col('row_num') == (count_bloom // 2) + 1) \
        .select('average_goals_per_match').collect()[0][0]

print(f"Moyenne (avec filtre de Bloom) : {mean_bloom}")
print(f"Médiane (avec filtre de Bloom) : {median_bloom}")
print(f"Variance (avec filtre de Bloom) : {variance_bloom}")

# Calcul de la moyenne et de la variance pour la méthode sans le filtre de Bloom
mean_no_bloom = top_clubs_by_year_exact.agg(F.mean('average_goals_per_match')).collect()[0][0]
variance_no_bloom = top_clubs_by_year_exact.agg(F.variance('average_goals_per_match')).collect()[0][0]

count_no_bloom = top_clubs_by_year_exact.count()

if count_no_bloom % 2 == 0:
    median_no_bloom = top_clubs_by_year_exact.withColumn('row_num', F.row_number().over(window_spec)) \
        .filter((F.col('row_num') == count_no_bloom // 2) | (F.col('row_num') == count_no_bloom // 2 + 1)) \
        .agg(F.mean('average_goals_per_match')).collect()[0][0]
else:
    median_no_bloom = top_clubs_by_year_exact.withColumn('row_num', F.row_number().over(window_spec)) \
        .filter(F.col('row_num') == (count_no_bloom // 2) + 1) \
        .select('average_goals_per_match').collect()[0][0]

print(f"Moyenne (sans filtre de Bloom) : {mean_no_bloom}")
print(f"Médiane (sans filtre de Bloom) : {median_no_bloom}")
print(f"Variance (sans filtre de Bloom) : {variance_no_bloom}")

Moyenne (avec filtre de Bloom) : 0.1260941905867409
Médiane (avec filtre de Bloom) : 0.08108108108108109
Variance (avec filtre de Bloom) : 0.022789639176610425
Moyenne (sans filtre de Bloom) : 2.1479713717845814
Médiane (sans filtre de Bloom) : 2.1578947368421053
Variance (sans filtre de Bloom) : 0.1933644139192156

1. Moyenne :¶

  • Avec le filtre de Bloom : La moyenne des buts par match est très faible (0.126).
  • Sans le filtre de Bloom : La moyenne est beaucoup plus élevée (2.15)
  • Pourquoi ? Le filtre de Bloom pourrait supprimer trop de game_id lors de la déduplication, ce qui entraînerait une sous-estimation du nombre de matchs, et donc une moyenne des buts par match beaucoup plus faible.

À l'inverse, la méthode sans le filtre de Bloom avec countDistinct semble plus fiable pour capturer les tendances réelles des données, car elle donne une moyenne plus raisonnable.

2. Médiane :¶

  • Avec le filtre de Bloom : La médiane est très basse (0.081), ce qui confirme que la majorité des observations sont faibles, renforçant l'idée que le filtre de Bloom pourrait éliminer trop de matchs.
  • Sans le filtre de Bloom : La médiane est très proche de la moyenne (2.16), ce qui montre que les données sont plus équilibrées sans la méthode du filtre de Bloom.

3. Variance :¶

  • Avec le filtre de Bloom : La variance est très faible (0.022), ce qui indique que les valeurs sont très proches les unes des autres et que les variations saisonnières sont presque inexistantes. Cela pourrait être dû à une réduction artificielle de la plage de données causée par l'élimination de trop de doublons.
  • Sans le filtre de Bloom : La variance est plus élevée (0.193), ce qui est logique compte tenu de la distribution plus large des buts moyens par match. Cela montre qu'il y a des variations significatives d'une saison à l'autre pour certains clubs, ce qui reflète mieux la réalité du football.

4. Temps d'éxécution :¶

  • 0.11 secondes pour le filtre de bloom
  • 0.27 secondes pour l'exact count

Conclusion :¶

  1. Le filtre de Bloom semble trop agressif dans l'élimination des doublons dans cette configuration. Cela pourrait être dû à une mauvaise configuration du filtre (capacité trop faible ou probabilité d'erreur trop élevée), entraînant la suppression de données valides malgré des résultats plus rapides.

  2. L'utilisation de countDistinct donne des résultats plus cohérents, avec des valeurs plus réalistes pour la moyenne, la médiane et la variance des buts par match. Dans ce cas précis, countDistinct est une méthode plus fiable pour gérer les doublons dans un temps relativement raisonnable.

  3. Malgré le temps d'éxécution plus rapide avec le filtre de bloom, l'utilisation du countDistinct semble clairement plus adapté.

Estimate home draw defeat win probability w/ Poisson law¶

for the first approach, i decided to estimate the draw, defeat or win probability using Poisson distribution. The probability is calculated based on the ajusted average goal of a team.

In [ ]:
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, lit, udf
from pyspark.sql.types import DoubleType, ArrayType
from scipy.stats import poisson
import numpy as np

# the average goals scored and conceded by each team
team_stats = df_cl.groupBy("home_club_id").agg(
    {'home_club_goals': 'avg', 'away_club_goals': 'avg'}
).withColumnRenamed("avg(home_club_goals)", "home_avg_goals_scored") \
 .withColumnRenamed("avg(away_club_goals)", "home_avg_goals_conceded")

# same for away teams
team_stats_away = df_cl.groupBy("away_club_id").agg(
    {'away_club_goals': 'avg', 'home_club_goals': 'avg'}
).withColumnRenamed("avg(away_club_goals)", "away_avg_goals_scored") \
 .withColumnRenamed("avg(home_club_goals)", "away_avg_goals_conceded")

# merge the home and away statistics
team_stats = team_stats.join(team_stats_away, team_stats.home_club_id == team_stats_away.away_club_id)

# we add value coefficients to the dataset to give more importance to scored goals than conceded ones.
coeff_scored = 1.29
coeff_conceded = 0.79

team_stats = team_stats.withColumn("adjusted_home_avg_goals_scored", col("home_avg_goals_scored") * coeff_scored) \
    .withColumn("adjusted_home_avg_goals_conceded", col("home_avg_goals_conceded") * coeff_conceded) \
    .withColumn("adjusted_away_avg_goals_scored", col("away_avg_goals_scored") * coeff_scored) \
    .withColumn("adjusted_away_avg_goals_conceded", col("away_avg_goals_conceded") * coeff_conceded)

Here we have the probabilitily for each team to score 0 to 4 goals when they are playing home or away. Usually the probability are higher when the team is home.

from pyspark.sql.functions import col, udf
from pyspark.sql.types import ArrayType, DoubleType
from scipy.stats import poisson

# udf function to calculate poisson probability (0 to 4 goals)
def poisson_probabilities(avg_goals):
    return [float(poisson.pmf(x, avg_goals)) for x in range(5)]

# register the udf
poisson_udf = udf(poisson_probabilities, ArrayType(DoubleType()))

# we apply it
team_stats = team_stats.withColumn("home_poisson_probs", poisson_udf(col("adjusted_home_avg_goals_scored"))) \
                       .withColumn("away_poisson_probs", poisson_udf(col("adjusted_away_avg_goals_scored")))

The create_probability_matrix function generates a 5x5 probability matrix (as we are dealing with 0 to 4 goals). Each element in the matrix represents the joint probability that the home team scores X goals and the away team scores Y goals. Since the probabilities are independent, each element in the matrix is calculated by multiplying the probability that the home team scores X goals by the probability that the away team scores Y goals. For example, matrix[0][0] represents the probability that both teams score 0 goals, and matrix[4][4] represents the probability that both teams score 4 goals. The matrix is then used to calculate the probabilities of a home win (sum of the elements below the diagonal), a draw (diagonal elements), and an away win (sum of the elements above the diagonal).

In [ ]:
def create_probability_matrix(home_probs, away_probs):
    matrix = []
    for home_prob in home_probs:
        row = []
        for away_prob in away_probs:
            row.append(home_prob * away_prob)  # Simply multiply the probabilities because independant
        matrix.append(row)
    return matrix

# register the UDF
probability_matrix_udf = udf(create_probability_matrix, ArrayType(ArrayType(DoubleType())))
team_stats = team_stats.withColumn("probability_matrix", probability_matrix_udf(col("home_poisson_probs"), col("away_poisson_probs")))

# UDF to calculate match outcomes probability for each team (home win, draw, away win)
def calculate_match_outcomes(matrix):
    home_win_prob = sum([sum(row[:i]) for i, row in enumerate(matrix)])  # sum of lower triangular matrix for home wins
    draw_prob = sum(matrix[i][i] for i in range(len(matrix)))  # diagonal for draws
    away_win_prob = sum([sum(row[i+1:]) for i, row in enumerate(matrix)])  # sum of upper triangular matrix for away wins
    return (home_win_prob, draw_prob, away_win_prob)

# register the UDF for match outcomes
match_outcomes_udf = udf(calculate_match_outcomes, ArrayType(DoubleType()))

# apply the UDF to calculate match outcomes (home win, draw, away win)
team_stats = team_stats.withColumn("match_outcomes", match_outcomes_udf(col("probability_matrix")))

The main problem of this approach is that we don't take in account the last result of a team (for example if the team is on a winning streak), we only consider the average. Elo is more adapted to take the last eprformances of a team in account.

Estimate home draw or win probability w/ Score Elo¶

from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, when, lit
import math

# first elo score
initial_elo = 1500

# we create a dictionnary of teams's info
team_info = {
    row["home_club_id"]: {
        "team_name": row["home_club_name"],
        "team_id": row["home_club_id"],
        "elo_score": initial_elo,
        "last_round": None,
        "last_year": None,
        "victories": 0
    }
    for row in df_cl.select("home_club_id", "home_club_name").distinct().collect()
}

# Broadcasting of elo's score dictionnary
broadcast_team_info = spark.sparkContext.broadcast(team_info)

# we get the probability of winning (E)
def expected_win(elo_a, elo_b):
    return 1 / (1 + 10**((elo_b - elo_a) / 400))

# function to update the elo score and the team's info
def update_team_info(home_team, away_team, home_goals, away_goals, season, round_name, is_win, broadcast_team_info):
    K = 20  # Factor K to adjust

    # get the current info
    home_info = broadcast_team_info.value.get(home_team)
    away_info = broadcast_team_info.value.get(away_team)

    # get the current score
    home_elo = home_info["elo_score"]
    away_elo = away_info["elo_score"]

    # calculate the proba
    E_home = expected_win(home_elo, away_elo)
    E_away = expected_win(away_elo, home_elo)

    # results
    if home_goals > away_goals:
        result_home = 1  # win
        result_away = 0
        home_info["victories"] += 1
    elif home_goals < away_goals:
        result_home = 0  # defeat
        result_away = 1
        away_info["victories"] += 1
    else:
        result_home = 0.5  # draw
        result_away = 0.5

    # Mise à jour des scores Elo
    new_home_elo = home_elo + K * (result_home - E_home)
    new_away_elo = away_elo + K * (result_away - E_away)

    # updating
    home_info["elo_score"] = new_home_elo
    away_info["elo_score"] = new_away_elo

    home_info["last_year"] = season
    away_info["last_year"] = season
    home_info["last_round"] = round_name
    away_info["last_round"] = round_name

    # updating the broadcast
    broadcast_team_info.value[home_team] = home_info
    broadcast_team_info.value[away_team] = away_info

# we order by
df = df_cl.orderBy(["season", "round", "date"])

for row in df.collect():
    update_team_info(
        row["home_club_id"],
        row["away_club_id"],
        row["home_club_goals"],
        row["away_club_goals"],
        row["season"],
        row["round"],
        row["is_win"],
        broadcast_team_info
    )

final_team_info = broadcast_team_info.value

from pyspark.sql.window import Window
from pyspark.sql.functions import row_number, col, desc, lit

# réunion des deux types de matchs (domicile et extérieur) dans une seule colonne
df_all_games = df_games.select(
    col("home_club_name").alias("team"),
    col("away_club_name").alias("opponent"),
    col("home_club_goals").alias("team_goals"),
    col("away_club_goals").alias("opponent_goals"),
    col("date"),
    col("competition_id"),
    lit("Home").alias("location")
).union(
    df_games.select(
        col("away_club_name").alias("team"),
        col("home_club_name").alias("opponent"),
        col("away_club_goals").alias("team_goals"),
        col("home_club_goals").alias("opponent_goals"),
        col("date"),
        col("competition_id"),
        lit("Away").alias("location")
    )
)

window_spec = Window.partitionBy("team").orderBy(desc("date"))
df_all_games_with_rank = df_all_games.withColumn("rank", row_number().over(window_spec))

# 5 derniers matchs pour chaque équipe
df_last_5_matches = df_all_games_with_rank.filter(
    (col("team").isin(teams)) & (col("rank") <= 5)
)

df_last_5_matches.show()

# récupérer le Broadcasting du dictionnaire des scores Elo
broadcast_team_info = spark.sparkContext.broadcast(team_info)

# udf similaires
def expected_win(elo_a, elo_b):
    return 1 / (1 + 10**((elo_b - elo_a) / 400))

def update_team_info(home_team, away_team, home_goals, away_goals, broadcast_team_info):
    K = 20
    default_elo = 1500

    home_info = broadcast_team_info.value.get(home_team)
    if home_info is None:
        home_info = {"team_name": home_team, "elo_score": default_elo, "victories": 0, "win_probability": None}
        broadcast_team_info.value[home_team] = home_info

    away_info = broadcast_team_info.value.get(away_team)
    if away_info is None:
        away_info = {"team_name": away_team, "elo_score": default_elo, "victories": 0, "win_probability": None}
        broadcast_team_info.value[away_team] = away_info

    home_elo = home_info["elo_score"]
    away_elo = away_info["elo_score"]

    E_home = expected_win(home_elo, away_elo)
    E_away = expected_win(away_elo, home_elo)

    if home_goals > away_goals:
        result_home = 1  # Victoire à domicile
        result_away = 0
        home_info["victories"] += 1
    elif home_goals < away_goals:
        result_home = 0  # Défaite à domicile
        result_away = 1
        away_info["victories"] += 1
    else:
        result_home = 0.5  # Match nul
        result_away = 0.5

    home_info["elo_score"] = home_elo + K * (result_home - E_home)
    away_info["elo_score"] = away_elo + K * (result_away - E_away)

    home_info["win_probability"] = E_home
    away_info["win_probability"] = E_away

    broadcast_team_info.value[home_team] = home_info
    broadcast_team_info.value[away_team] = away_info

import socket
import random
import json
import time
from threading import Thread

teams = [
    "Arsenal Football Club", "Aston Villa Football Club", "Atalanta Bergamasca Calcio S.p.a.",
    "Club Atlético de Madrid S.A.D.", "Borussia Dortmund", "Futbol Club Barcelona",
    "FC Bayern München", "Sport Lisboa e Benfica", "Bologna Football Club 1909", "Stade brestois 29",
    "The Celtic Football Club", "Club Brugge Koninklijke Voetbalvereniging",
    "Feyenoord Rotterdam", "Girona Fútbol Club S. A. D.", "Football Club Internazionale Milano S.p.A.",
    "Juventus Football Club", "RasenBallsport Leipzig", "Bayer 04 Leverkusen Fußball",
    "Lille Olympique Sporting Club Lille Métropole", "Liverpool Football Club",
    "Manchester City Football Club", "Associazione Calcio Milan", "Association sportive de Monaco Football Club",
    "Paris Saint-Germain Football Club", "Eindhovense Voetbalvereniging Philips Sport Vereniging",
    "Real Madrid Club de Fútbol", "Sporting Clube de Portugal", "Verein für Bewegungsspiele Stuttgart 1893"
]

def generate_random_match():
    home_team = random.choice(teams)
    away_team = random.choice(teams)
    while away_team == home_team:
        away_team = random.choice(teams)

    match_data = {
        "home_team": home_team,
        "away_team": away_team,
        "home_goals": random.randint(0, 5),
        "away_goals": random.randint(0, 5),
        "season": 2024,
    }
    return json.dumps(match_data)

def start_socket_server(host='localhost', port=8858):
    server_socket = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)
    server_socket.bind((host, port))
    server_socket.listen(1)
    print(f"Server listening on {host}:{port}")

    conn, addr = server_socket.accept()
    print(f"Connection from {addr}")

    try:
        while True:
            match_data = generate_random_match()
            conn.sendall((match_data + "\n").encode('utf-8'))  # Send match data as a line
            time.sleep(2)  # Send data every 2 seconds
    except KeyboardInterrupt:
        print("Server stopped.")
    finally:
        conn.close()
        server_socket.close()

# Start the server in a background thread
server_thread = Thread(target=start_socket_server)
server_thread.start()

from pyspark.sql.functions import from_json, col
from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType

# Schéma pour les données JSON
json_schema = StructType([
    StructField("home_team", StringType(), True),
    StructField("away_team", StringType(), True),
    StructField("home_goals", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("away_goals", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("season", IntegerType(), True)
])

# Fonction de traitement de chaque batch
def process_batch(batch_df, batch_id):
    # Extraire et parser les données JSON
    parsed_batch_df = batch_df.withColumn("parsed_json", from_json(col("value"), json_schema))

    # Sélectionner les colonnes pertinentes
    df_structured = parsed_batch_df.select(
        col("parsed_json.home_team").alias("home_team"),
        col("parsed_json.away_team").alias("away_team"),
        col("parsed_json.home_goals").alias("home_goals"),
        col("parsed_json.away_goals").alias("away_goals")
    )

    # Mettre à jour les scores Elo pour chaque ligne du batch
    for row in df_structured.collect():
        update_team_info(
            row["home_team"],
            row["away_team"],
            row["home_goals"],
            row["away_goals"],
            broadcast_team_info
        )

    # Créer un DataFrame temporaire avec les équipes qualifiées et leurs scores Elo mis à jour
    updated_teams = [(team, info["team_name"], info["elo_score"], info["victories"], info["win_probability"])
                     for team, info in broadcast_team_info.value.items() if team in teams]

    df_updated_elo = spark.createDataFrame(updated_teams, schema=["team_id", "team_name", "elo_score", "victories", "win_probability"])
    df_updated_elo.createOrReplaceTempView("elo_updates_via_socket")
